<subSubSection pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,799,896]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
Originally described as 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1884" box="[464,701,836,861]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Lasiochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Dilasia">
<emphasis box="[464,701,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Lasiochilus (Dilasia)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The “spines on legs” and the “not so deeply dotted clavus” (as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1900" box="[151,328,872,896]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Lasiochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctipennis">
<emphasis box="[151,328,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">D. punctipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) mentioned in the original description, show that they belong to the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Reuter, 1871" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1871" box="[1168,1250,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Dilasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1168,1250,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Dilasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
